@node Introduction, Acknowledgements, Copying, Top
@unnumbered Introduction

You are reading about af, an advanced, self-documenting, customisable,
real-time display-oriented mail reader and composer.  If you think that
sounds rather like the Emacs editor, you're correct; af is designed to
follow the Emacs paradigm as closely as possible.

We say that af is @dfn{display-oriented} because normally the messages
being read are visible on the screen and are updated automatically as
you type your commands.  @xref{Screen,Display}.

We call it a @dfn{real-time} mail reader because the display is updated
very frequently, usually after each character or pair of characters you
type.  This minimises the amount of information you must keep in your
head as you process your mail.  @xref{Basics}.

We call af advanced because it provides facilities that go beyond
simple reading of messages: viewing multiple mail folders at once,
searching and sorting mailboxes, and dealing with groups of messages
in one operation.

Similarly, we have tried to take care that af complies with any relevant
standards: it conforms closely to @sc{rfc822}, the Internet Standard for
Mail Messages, and will work with such standard Mail Transfer Agents as
@sc{uucp}, sendmail, and @sc{mmdf}; and supports the @sc{pop3} protocol
for reading mail from a remote server.  Af also has limited support for
@sc{mime} mail, which we hope to improve in the future
@footnote{Don't worry if you don't understand this; you don't need to
know about these things to use af}.

@dfn{Self-documenting} means that help about af is available from
within af itself.  You can find out what any command does, or find
all the commands that are relevant to a topic.  @xref{Help}.

@dfn{Customisable} means that you can change the definitions of af
commands in little ways.  For example, if you prefer to include the text
of the original message into the text of a reply to that message, then
you can tell af to do so.  Another sort of customisation is
rearrangement of the command set.  For example, if you prefer the four
basic cursor motion commands (up, down, left and right) on keys in a
diamond pattern on the keyboard, you can rebind the keys that way.
@xref{Customisation}.

